<section class="prose">
  <h1>About Eleven</h1>
  <p class="updated">The honest status quo, on one page — with everything deeper linked from here.</p>

  <h2>What this is</h2>
  <p>
    Eleven is a group chat messenger for families, communities, and
    businesses. It exists because a kid couldn't message their friends
    without a phone number, an account, or an advertising business
    attached — <a href="/story/">that's the story</a> — and it's built by
    two dads who've each spent decades making software for the web.
  </p>

  <h2>How it was built</h2>
  <p>
    Here's the part that raises eyebrows, so we'll say it plainly: Eleven
    went from nothing to a working product — a live service, a web app,
    native Mac and iPhone apps, end-to-end encryption from the very first
    message — in about two weeks, built by two people working with AI. An
    AI fever dream, with a download button.
  </p>

  <h2>Why it might matter</h2>
  <p>
    The speed is the least of it. The way Eleven is built and run looks
    like a genuinely new way to make planet-scale software: rapidly,
    cheaply, and without the usual compromises — on privacy, on
    efficiency, on who owns the thing. &ldquo;Looks like&rdquo; is
    deliberate: it's early, and claims that size need checking. So rather
    than ask you to take the claim, we publish the working — the
    architecture, the carbon arithmetic, the live fleet — in the pages
    below.
  </p>
  <p>
    Two commitments hold it together. Everything is designed to
    <strong>outlive AI</strong>: plain, readable code that a small human
    team could carry on maintaining if AI got expensive or disappeared.
    And the destination is a <strong>co-operative</strong>: owned by the
    people who use and run it, with open books and no exit.
  </p>
</section>

